{{nihongo|''Hanjuku Hero 4: 7-Nin no Hanjuku Hero''|半熟英雄4 ～7人の半熟英雄～||"Hanjuku Hero 4: The 7 Hanjuku Heroes"}} was released for the [[PlayStation 2]] in Japan on April 26, 2005. It was released in a normal edition as well as a limited edition titled {{nihongo|''Hanjuku Ginga Bentō''|半熟銀河弁当||Hanjuku Galaxy Lunch}} which contained a lunch box and promotional items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://watch.impress.co.jp/game%2Fdocs/20050407/hanjuk.htm|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20050409011920/http://watch.impress.co.jp/game%2Fdocs/20050407/hanjuk.htm |archive-date=April 9, 2005|date=May 15, 2020|title=スクウェア・エニックス、PS2「半熟英雄4」、限定版「半熟銀河弁当」のパッケージと特典を公開}}</ref> In this game, Lord Almamoon discovers that he has been tricked into marrying the princess of the Katri Kingdom, who is considered to be the ugliest woman in the world.<ref name="HH4"/> The game contains two types of battles: 100 on 100 battle using a mix of 2D and 3D, and three-on-three party-based Egg Monster vs. Egg Monster battles.<ref>{{cite web | author=Jackson, Jordan | date=February 28, 2005 | title=Kamera no Kitamura | url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/japan/jj022805.html | work=RPGamer.com | access-date=2008-12-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709020956/http://www.rpgamer.com/news/japan/jj022805.html | archive-date=July 9, 2008 | url-status=dead}}</ref>

Composers [[Nobuo Uematsu]], [[Kenji Ito]], [[Tsuyoshi Sekito]], Hirosato Noda, [[Naoshi Mizuta]], and Ai Yamashita did the soundtrack of the game. Uematsu has a [[cameo appearance]] within the game, along with Sekito and [[Kenichiro Fukui]], both of whom were members of his former band, [[The Black Mages]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Niizumi |first=Hirohiko |title=Uematsu's Hanjuku plans will make fans smile |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/uematsus-hanjuku-plans-will-make-fans-smile/1100-6116820/ |publisher=GameSpot |access-date=2016-01-29 |date=2005-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Winkler, Chris | date=January 21, 2005 | title=Hanjuku Eiyuu 4 Composers Revealed | url=http://www.rpgfan.com/news/2005/1076.html | work=RPGFan.com | access-date=2008-12-20 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070510095636/http://www.rpgfan.com/news/2005/1076.html | archive-date=May 10, 2007 | url-status=live}}</ref> The limited edition of the game came with a two-disc soundtrack album for the game, titled ''Hanjuku Hero 4 - The 7 Heroes- ~Sound Collection~''. The album contains 43 tracks and covers a duration of 1:51:42.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gann |first=Patrick |title=Hanjuku Hero 4 - The 7 Heroes- ~Sound Collection~ |url=http://www.rpgfan.com/soundtracks/hanjukuhero4/index.html |access-date=2011-05-11 |date=2005-10-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213214622/http://rpgfan.com/soundtracks/hanjukuhero4/index.html |archive-date=2011-12-13 |url-status=live}}</ref>

==Reception==
Review scores of the ''Hanjuku Hero'' series have been fairly good. The Japanese magazine ''[[Famitsu]]'' has scored the WonderSwan version of ''Hanjuku Hero: Aa, Sekaiyo Hanjukunare...!'' a 30.<ref>''ワンダースワン - 半熟英雄 ああ、世界よ半熟なれ・・・!!''. Weekly Famitsu. No.915 Pt.2. Pg.113. 30 June 2006.</ref>

By February 1994, sales of the first two ''Hanjuku Hero'' games had totaled 400,000 units in Japan.<ref name=sales2>{{cite journal | title=The ''Secret of Mana''{{'}}s Success | author=Kai, Norton | issue=9 | date=February 1994 | pages=16, 17 | journal=SNES Force}}</ref>

''Hanjuku Hero Tai 3D'' was the second best-selling game on the day of its release at 49,904 copies.<ref>{{cite web | author=Winkler, Chris | title=Hanjuku Hero VS 3D and Viorate no Atelier Sales | url=http://www.rpgfan.com/news/2003/1660.html | work=RPGFan.com | date=2003-06-27 | access-date=2008-12-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524042636/http://www.rpgfan.com/news/2003/1660.html | archive-date=2011-05-24 | url-status=live}}</ref> The game sold over 169,000 copies during 2003.<ref>{{cite web | title=2003 Top 100 Best Selling Japanese Console Games | url=http://the-magicbox.com/Chart-BestSell2003b.shtml | work=The-MagicBox.com | access-date=2008-12-21 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414115019/http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-BestSell2003b.shtml | archive-date=2012-04-14 | url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Egg Monster Hero'' debuted on the Japanese ''[[ASCII Media Works|Dengeki]]'' sales charts at number 6 during the week of its release and stayed in the top 50 until the week of May 31, 2005.<ref>{{cite web | author=Jackson, Jordan | date=May 31, 2005 | title=Culture Shock | url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/japan/pc053105.html | publisher=RPGamer | access-date=2008-12-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006194024/http://www.rpgamer.com/news/japan/pc053105.html | archive-date=October 6, 2008 | url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=Jackson, Jordan | date=April 4, 2005 | title=Konnichiwa | url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/japan/jj040405.html | work=RPGamer | access-date=2008-12-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709022402/http://www.rpgamer.com/news/japan/jj040405.html | archive-date=July 9, 2008 | url-status=dead}}</ref> The game has managed to sell approximately 92,096 copies as of November 2008.<ref>{{cite web | title=Nintendo DS Japanese Ranking | url=http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/ds.php | work=Japan-GameCharts.com | access-date=2008-12-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808100144/http://www.japan-gamecharts.com/ds.php | archive-date=2008-08-08 | url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Media Create]] sales data suggests that ''Hanjuku Hero 4'' sold around 42,819 copies by the week ending on June 5, 2005.<ref>{{cite web | author=Bayer, Glen | date=June 14, 2005 | title=[Japa-N] Sales data; info on Lunar and Goemon | url=http://www.n-sider.com/contentview.php?contentid=1329 | work=N-Sider.com | access-date=2008-12-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611041402/http://www.n-sider.com/contentview.php?contentid=1329 | archive-date=June 11, 2011 | url-status=live}}</ref>

